      All INTERF IDs "LL-INTERF-6.1.1", "LL-INTERF-6.1.2", "LL-INTERF-6.1.3", "LL-INTERF-6.2.1", "LL-INTERF-6.2.2", "LL-INTERF-6.2.3" have an extra numeric segment.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Rename to valid IDs, for example:
      - LL-INTERF-6.1.1 → LL-INTERF-6.1
      - LL-INTERF-6.1.2 → LL-INTERF-6.2
      - LL-INTERF-6.1.3 → LL-INTERF-6.3
      - LL-INTERF-6.2.1 → LL-INTERF-7.1
      - LL-INTERF-6.2.2 → LL-INTERF-7.2
      - LL-INTERF-6.2.3 → LL-INTERF-7.3
      or a similar consistent scheme.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--23">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.1.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      Requirement LL-EXPL-1.1.3 is typed as "NFR" but its content ("The system shall execute its main control loop ... at a minimum frequency of 20 Hz") describes a concrete behavior and processing flow (sensor acquisition, estimation, mapping updates, planning, command generation). This is more characteristic of a functional requirement than a pure constraint.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Reclassify the Type from "NFR" to "FR", or split it into:
      - an FR describing the existence and structure of the main control loop,
      - an NFR specifying the required minimum loop frequency (e.g. &gt;= 20 Hz).
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--24">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.1.4</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      Requirement LL-EXPL-1.1.4 uses the phrase "within the available physical memory defined for the target platform" without specifying a concrete numeric limit. This leaves room for ambiguity and may hinder strict testability.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Replace the vague reference with a concrete bound, for example:
      "… shall limit its RAM usage to at most {X} MB on the target platform" or reference a clearly versioned platform specification that defines the exact physical memory and allowed percentage.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--25">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-2.1.5</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      LL-MAP-2.1.5 ("The map subsystem shall support storing at least a maze of 32 by 32 cells …") uses "the map subsystem shall", whereas the policy recommends framing requirements uniformly from the system perspective and may create ambiguity whether this is a separate subsystem or the same system.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Rephrase to maintain consistency and clarity, e.g.:
      "The system shall support storing at least a maze of 32 by 32 cells …" or explicitly define "map subsystem" in the glossary and then consistently reference it.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--26">
    <ItemID>LL-RUN-4.2.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      LL-RUN-4.2.2 refers to a "target cell", but the corresponding HLRs do not define how the target is specified (by user input, by rules such as 'maze exit', etc.). This can cause ambiguity at architecture and design time.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add or refine a requirement (HLR or LLR) that defines how the target cell is determined or provided (e.g., via user input, preconfigured coordinates, detection of a goal marker), and then reference that requirement from LL-RUN-4.2.2.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--27">
    <ItemID>HL-EXPL-1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The HLR "HL-EXPL-1.1 Example" is effectively a placeholder with non-specific content. The LLRs LL-EXPL-1.1.1 through LL-EXPL-1.1.5 refine it with substantial system-level behavior (initialization, mode selection, main loop, resource limits, logging). However, because the HLR itself is not a clear, testable system capability and is labeled "Example Description", it is not truly refined; instead, the LLRs introduce new capabilities that are not traceable to a meaningful HLR intent. This violates the traceability rule that “every part of any Low-level requirement must be traceable to a refined High-level requirement” and that HLRs must be testable and implementable system capabilities.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Replace HL-EXPL-1.1 with a concrete, testable high-level requirement describing the intended system capability (e.g., "The system shall provide an autonomous exploration operating mode including initialization, control loop execution, and logging.") and ensure its content clearly justifies the LLRs it is refined into. Adjust wording or relationships of the affected LLRs if necessary so they fully and exclusively refine the clarified HLR.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--28">
    <ItemID>GLOBAL-ARCH</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      While the set of LLRs is generally detailed and covers major exploration, mapping, planning, reliability, and interfacing aspects, several critical architectural cross-cutting concerns are only implicitly defined, which may hinder straightforward architecture design:
      - No explicit requirement for overall module decomposition (e.g. separate "Exploration Controller", "Mapping Module", "Motion Controller", "Collision Avoidance Layer"), even though these are implicitly referenced.
      - No explicit requirement about inter-module communication patterns (e.g. event-based vs polling, data bus).
      - No explicit requirement for error handling and state transitions at the system level (beyond local mentions like "Error" state in exploration and sensor fault behavior).
      Architecture can still be derived, but adding explicit LLRs for these concerns would make the design step more direct and less assumption-driven.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add a small number of additional LLRs (e.g., under EXPL or a new SYS category) that:
      - Define the main runtime components/modules and their responsibilities at a coarse level (e.g., "The system shall be decomposed into modules for exploration control, mapping, planning, motion control, collision avoidance, and logging, each with clearly defined interfaces.").
      - Specify the main communication/interaction style (e.g., "The system shall exchange data between modules via shared data structures with producer/consumer interfaces" or via a message bus).
      - Define global error-handling behavior and transitions between global operating modes (startup, exploration, second run, error, shutdown).
    </Solution>
  </Finding>
</Findings>
